// `HostState::next_ensures(old_self, old_netc, new_self, new_netc, rc)`
// is genuinely relational in `(new_self, new_netc, rc)`: its body invokes
// `Self::next(old_self.view(), new_self.view(), res@.ios)`, which is
// `pub open spec fn next(pre, post, ios) -> bool { ... exists |step|
// next_step(pre, post, ios, step) ... }`.  Both `step` (the host-step
// discriminator) and `ios` (the network trace) are existentially chosen,
// so two runs from the same pre-state can legitimately produce different
// `(new_self, new_netc, rc)` tuples that both satisfy `next_ensures`.
//
// Concretely, `real_next_impl` performs a `NetClient::receive`, whose
// observable output is non-deterministic; the spec witnesses this by
// existentially binding `ios` (and the entire history extension) inside
// `next_ensures`.  Consequently `det_real_next_impl_equal` cannot be
// derived from a pair of `next_ensures` instances without an unsound
// axiom — there is no sound `lemma_next_ensures_functional`-style
// uniqueness lemma to prove either, since the underlying `next` relation
// is itself non-functional.
//
// Every statement below is a direct, sound consequence of the
// `next_requires` hypothesis (which is the only fact this prelude can
// soundly add).  They are emitted only to align triggers and to give a
// minimal, lex-clean prelude; they cannot — and do not pretend to —
// close the determinism gap, which is fundamentally not valid.
assert(pre_self_.invariants(&pre_netc.my_end_point()));
assert(pre_netc.state() is Receiving);
